<p><big><font color="#800000"><big><b>Fresnel Diffraction, Circular Aperture: Theory</b> </big></font></big><br>
<big><font color="#008040"><b>Fresnel Zones</b></font></big></p>

<p>The stunning nature of the above results seems to imply that there is something
physically significant about the Fresnel number. The Fig. 2 below shows a side view of the
system. The point <i>O</i> is the origin (it is at the center of the aperture), <i>P</i>
is the observation point, and <i>Q</i> is a point in the aperture which is a distance <font FACE="Symbol">r</font> <font FACE="Symbol">¢</font> from <i>O</i>. </p>
<div align="center"><center>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="80%">
  <tr>
    <td width="100%"><p align="center"><img src="../images/figure2.gif" alt="figure2.gif (1258 bytes)" WIDTH="338" HEIGHT="237"></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td width="100%"><small>Fig. 2 Geometry for an on-axis observation point.</small></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</center></div>

<p>The path length difference between the spherical wave arriving at <i>P</i> from <i>Q</i>
and the spherical wave arriving at <i>P</i> from <i>O</i> is</p>
<div align="center"><center>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="80%">
  <tr>
    <td width="80%"><p align="center"><img src="../images/cir-theory13.gif" WIDTH="128" HEIGHT="53"></td>
    <td width="20%"><p align="right">(<a name="3.1">3.1</a>)</td>
  </tr>
</table>
</center></div><div align="center"><center>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="80%">
  <tr>
    <td width="80%"></td>
    <td width="20%"><p align="right"><a href="javascript:history.go(-1)"><img src="../../images/back.gif" alt="back2.gif (135 bytes)" hspace="5" border="0" WIDTH="35" HEIGHT="10"></a></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</center></div>

<p>where <i>d</i> is the distance from <i>Q</i> to <i>P.</i></p>

<p>Let us now draw circles inside the aperture (and centered about <i>O</i>) of radii <i><font FACE="Symbol">r</font>'</i><sub>1</sub>, <i><font FACE="Symbol">r</font>'</i><sub>2</sub>,
<i><font FACE="Symbol">r</font>'</i><sub>3</sub>, &#133;such that the spherical wave from
the nth circle travels a distance <i>n<font FACE="Symbol">l</font></i>/2 further than the
spherical wave emanating from <i>O</i> (in order to get to the point <i>P</i>), i.e.,</p>
<div align="center"><center>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="80%">
  <tr>
    <td width="80%"><p align="center"><img src="../images/cir-theory14.gif" WIDTH="249" HEIGHT="32"></td>
    <td width="20%"><p align="right">(<a name="3.2">3.2</a>)</td>
  </tr>
</table>
</center></div><div align="center"><center>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="80%">
  <tr>
    <td width="80%"></td>
    <td width="20%"><p align="right"><a href="javascript:history.go(-1)"><img src="../../images/back.gif" alt="back2.gif (135 bytes)" hspace="5" border="0" WIDTH="35" HEIGHT="10"></a></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</center></div>

<p>We have now divided the aperture into a particular set of annuli (except for the first
region which is a disk): its <font color="#0000FF"><b>Fresnel zones</b></font>. An
approximate formula for the radius of the m<sup>th</sup> Fresnel zone can be obtained in
the following way. It follows from Eq. (3.2) that</p>
<div align="center"><center>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="80%">
  <tr>
    <td width="80%"><p align="center"><img src="../images/cir-theory16.gif" WIDTH="190" HEIGHT="26"></td>
    <td width="20%"><p align="right">(<a name="3.3">3.3</a>)</td>
  </tr>
</table>
</center></div><div align="center"><center>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="80%">
  <tr>
    <td width="80%"></td>
    <td width="20%"><p align="right"><a href="javascript:history.go(-1)"><img src="../../images/back.gif" alt="back2.gif (135 bytes)" hspace="5" border="0" WIDTH="35" HEIGHT="10"></a></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</center></div>

<p>For reasonable values of <i>z</i>, <i>n</i>, and <font FACE="Symbol">l</font> the third
term on the right hand side of Eq. (3.3 ) is negligibly small compared to the other two
terms on that side, and we find that to a good approximation,</p>
<div align="center"><center>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="80%">
  <tr>
    <td width="80%"><p align="center"><img src="../images/cir-theory17.gif" WIDTH="73" HEIGHT="26"></td>
    <td width="20%"><p align="right">(<a name="3.4">3.4</a>)</td>
  </tr>
</table>
</center></div><div align="center"><center>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="80%">
  <tr>
    <td width="80%"></td>
    <td width="20%"><p align="right"><a href="javascript:history.go(-1)"><img src="../../images/back.gif" alt="back2.gif (135 bytes)" hspace="5" border="0" WIDTH="35" HEIGHT="10"></a></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</center></div>

<p>It follows from Eqs. (<a href="2.html#2.2">2.2</a>) and (3.4) that the
Fresnel number, <font color="#0000FF"><b>N tells us the number of Fresnel zones that are
contributing to the field at <i>P</i></b></font>. Fig. 3 below shows twelve Fresnel zones
whose radii were calculated with Eq. (3.4).</p>
<div align="center"><center>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="80%">
  <tr>
    <td width="100%"><p align="center"><img src="../images/fresnel-s.gif" WIDTH="245" HEIGHT="244"><a onmouseover="window.status='Enlarge Figure'; return true" href="javascript:imageWindow('../images/fresnel.gif')"><img src="../images/mag2.gif" border="0" WIDTH="20" HEIGHT="20"></a></td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td width="100%"><small>Fig. 3 The first twelve Fresnel zones.</small></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</center></div>

<p>We are now in a position to understand the results (a) and (b) above. Let us calculate
the electric field, call it <i>E<sub>n</sub></i>(0,z), at the point P due to the nth
Fresnel zone. It follows from Eq. (<a href="2.html#2.1">2.1</a>) that</p>
<div align="center"><center>

<table border="0" cellpadding="0" cellspacing="0" width="80%">
  <tr>
    <td width="80%"><p align="center"><img src="../images/cir-theory19.gif" WIDTH="334" HEIGHT="53"></td>
    <td width="20%"><p align="right">(<a name="3.5">3.5</a>)</td>
  </tr>
  <tr>
    <td width="80%"></td>
    <td width="20%"><p align="right"><a href="javascript:history.go(-1)"><img src="../../images/back.gif" alt="back2.gif (135 bytes)" hspace="5" border="0" WIDTH="35" HEIGHT="10"></a></td>
  </tr>
</table>
</center></div>

<p>This result shows that <font color="#0000FF"><b>each Fresnel zone contributes, at <i>P</i>,
an electric field of the same amplitude (</b>2<i>E<sub>0i</sub></i>) <b>and the fields
from consecutive zones are <font FACE="Symbol">p</font> out of phase with each other</font>.</b>
That is the reason why an even number of zones gives us zero intensity at P, and an odd
number of zones gives us an intensity of 4<i>I<sub>i</sub></i>.</p>

